         <p>To transition from direct variation to <em>Inverse Variation</em>, we move from relationships that grow together to relationships that "balance" each other. This experience uses a physical, hands-on approach to help learners discover that as one value increases, the other must decrease to maintain a constant product.</p>

    <activity>
        <statement>
           

            <title>Learner Experience 1.2.1: The Rectangle Challenge</title>

            <p><em>Objective:</em> To discover the relationship between the length and width of rectangles with a fixed area.</p>

            <title>Work in Groups</title>

            <p><em>What you need:</em></p>
            <ul>
                <li>24 small identical square tiles (or draw 24 equal squares on graph paper).</li>
                <li>A ruler and pencil.</li>
                <li>A table to record your observations.</li>
            </ul>

            <title>What to do</title>

            <p><em>(a) Physical Arrangement</em></p>
            <p>Your task is to arrange all <em>24 tiles</em> into a single solid rectangle. Each time you find a new way to arrange them, measure the <em>Length (L)</em> and the <em>Width (W)</em>. </p>
            <p><em>Start with a width of 1 unit and work your way up.</em></p>

            <p><em>(b) Data Collection</em></p>
            <p>Record the dimensions of every possible rectangle you can make using exactly 24 tiles.</p>

            <table>
                <tabular>
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Rectangle</cell>
                        <cell>Width (x)</cell>
                        <cell>Length (y)</cell>
                        <cell>Product (x × y)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>A</cell>
                        <cell>1</cell>
                        <cell>24</cell>
                        <cell>1 × 24 = 24</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>B</cell>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell>12</cell>
                        <cell>2 × 12 = 24</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>C</cell>
                        <cell>3</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>D</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>E</cell>
                        <cell>6</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>F</cell>
                        <cell>8</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>

            <title>Analysis &amp; Discovery</title>

            <p><em>(c) Observing the Opposite</em></p>
            <p>Look at your table. As the <em>Width (x)</em> increases (gets larger), what happens to the <em>Length (y)</em>?</p>
            <ul>
                <li>When the width is 1, the length is 24.</li>
                <li>When the width is 2, the length is 12.</li>
                <li>As you continue, you will see that as the width increases, the length decreases.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><em>(d) Defining the Constant</em></p>
            <p>In Direct Variation, the <em>ratio</em>  (y/x)  was constant. In this activity, what stays the same?</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Notice that x × y always equals <em>24</em>.</li>
                <li>This "magic number" 24 is our <em>Constant of Proportionality (k)</em>.</li>
            </ul>

            <blockquote>
                <p><em>The Inverse Rule:</em> y = k/x or xy = k</p>
            </blockquote>

            <p><em>(e) Share and Reflect</em></p>
            <p>Compare your findings with your group:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><em>The Trend:</em> If you wanted a rectangle with a width of <em>24</em>, how long would it be?</li>
                <li><em>The Graph:</em> If you plotted these points, would they form a straight line? (Try connecting the points (1,24), (2,12), (3,8) on your graph paper).</li>
                <li><em>Real-World Link:</em> Think of a pile of soil. If more people work to move it, what happens to the time taken? Does this follow the same pattern as your tiles?</li>
            </ol>

            <p> Inverse Variation, as one variable doubles, the other halves!</p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

