   <insight>
    <p>Inverse variation occurs when the product of two variables is a constant. Mathematically, we express this relationship as y = k/x or xy = k, where y and x are the variables and k is the constant of proportionality.</p>
    
    (<p>
      <em>The Graphical Signature</em>  
    </p>
    <p>Unlike direct variation, the graph of an inverse relationship is never a straight line. It forms a curve known as a hyperbola.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>The curve gets closer and closer to the x and y axes but never actually touches them.</li>
        <li>As x increases, the drop in y is sharp at first and then becomes more gradual.</li>
        <li>The graph never passes through (0,0) because you cannot divide by zero.</li>
    </ul>

    <em>Example: Speed and Time</em>
    <p>A classic real-world example is the relationship between speed s and time t taken to cover a fixed distance d:</p>
    <p>s = d/t</p>
    <p>Comparing to y = k/x gives:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Speed s is the y variable.</li>
        <li>Time t is the x variable.</li>
        <li>Distance d is the constant k.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>For a fixed distance of 100 km:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>At 100 km/h, it takes 1 hour. (100 × 1 = 100)</li>
        <li>At 50 km/h, it takes 2 hours. (50 × 2 = 100)</li>
        <li>At 25 km/h, it takes 4 hours. (25 × 4 = 100)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>As the speed halves, the time doubles. The product remains 100.</p>

    <term>Difference Between Direct and Inverse Variation</term>
    
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Feature</cell>
                <cell>Direct Variation</cell>
                <cell>Inverse Variation</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Equation</cell>
                <cell>y = kx</cell>
                <cell>y = k/x</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Relation</cell>
                <cell>y/x = k (Constant Ratio)</cell>
                <cell>xy = k (Constant Product)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Graph</cell>
                <cell>Straight line through origin</cell>
                <cell>Curve (Hyperbola)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Visual Trend</cell>
                <cell>Both go up together</cell>
                <cell>One goes up, the other goes down</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    
    <p>In inverse variation, the total amount (k) is fixed. If you want to change one factor, the other must adapt to keep that total the same.</p>
</insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>It is known that <m>y \propto \frac{1}{x}</m>. If <m>y = 20</m> when <m>x = 3</m>, find <m>y</m> when <m>x = \frac{1}{2}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): <m>y = \frac{k}{x} \implies k = y \times x</m>. <m>k = 20 \times 3 = 60</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Find <m>y</m>: <m>y = \frac{60}{1/2}</m> <m>y = 60 \times 2</m></p>
                    <p><m>y = 120</m></p></li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Given that <m>p \propto \frac{1}{q}</m> and that when <m>p = 8, q = 25</m>, find:</p>
            <p>(a) the equation connecting <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>.</p>
            <p>(b) <m>p</m> when <m>q = 10</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>(a) <m>k = p \times q = 8 \times 25 = 200</m>.</p>
            <p>Equation: <m>p = \frac{200}{q}</m></p>
            <p>(b) <m>p = \frac{200}{10}</m></p>
            <p><m>p = 20</m></p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>A quantity <m>y</m> varies inversely as a quantity <m>x</m>. Copy and complete the table:</p>
            <tabular halign="center">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell>2</cell>
                    <cell>4</cell>
                    <cell>8</cell>
                    <cell>16</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell>16</cell>
                    <cell>—</cell>
                    <cell>—</cell>
                    <cell>2</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>(a) Find the constant of proportionality.</p>
            <p>(b) Describe the shape of the graph if <m>y</m> is plotted against <m>x</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Constant: Using <m>(2, 16)</m>, <m>k = 2 \times 16 = 32</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Missing values: For <m>x=4, y=32/4 = 8</m>. For <m>x=8, y=32/8 = 4</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Graph Shape: A plot of <m>y</m> against <m>x</m> forms a <em>rectangular hyperbola</em> (a smooth curve that approaches the axes but never touches them).</p></li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The data below follows the relationship <m>y = \frac{k}{x}</m>.</p>
            <tabular halign="center">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>2</cell>
                    <cell>5</cell>
                    <cell>10</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>1/x</m></cell>
                    <cell>1.0</cell>
                    <cell>0.5</cell>
                    <cell>0.2</cell>
                    <cell>0.1</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell>50</cell>
                    <cell>25</cell>
                    <cell>10</cell>
                    <cell>5</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>If you were to draw a graph of <m>y</m> against <m>\frac{1}{x}</m>, what would be the gradient (slope) of the resulting line?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Relationship: The equation <m>y = \frac{k}{x}</m> can be written as <m>y = k(\frac{1}{x})</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Identify <m>k</m>: <m>k = y \times x = 50 \times 1 = 50</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Interpretation: When <m>y</m> is plotted against <m>\frac{1}{x}</m>, the graph is a straight line through the origin with gradient <m>k</m>.</p>
                    <p>The gradient is 50.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The pressure (<m>P</m>) of a gas varies inversely as the volume (<m>V</m>). When <m>V = 10, P = 2</m>.</p>
            <p>(a) Find the equation relating <m>P</m> and <m>V</m>.</p>
            <p>(b) If the volume is doubled, what happens to the pressure? Show this using the graph.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>(a) <m>k = 10 \times 2 = 20</m>. Equation: <m>P = \frac{20}{V}</m></p>
            <p>(b) If <m>V</m> doubles (e.g., from 10 to 20):</p>
            <p><m>P = \frac{20}{20} = 1</m>.</p>
            <p>The pressure is halved. On the graph, as you move further right along the x-axis (Volume), the y-value (Pressure) drops proportionally toward the axis.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

